I'm using the webpack compiler API with memfs to bundle the dependencies of a website.

One of the files being included in the bundle is the following from framer-motion:

```javascript
// file: /site/node_modules/framer-motion/dist/es/context/LazyContext.mjs

import { createContext } from 'react';

var LazyContext = createContext({ strict: false });

export { LazyContext };
```

The bundled output of that file is as follows. Note the broken use of `undefined` as the function in the second to last line:

```javascript
/***/ "/site/node_modules/framer-motion/dist/es/context/LazyContext.mjs":
/*!**********************************************************************************************************!*\
  !*** /site/node_modules/framer-motion/dist/es/context/LazyContext.mjs ***!
  \**********************************************************************************************************/
/*! exports provided: LazyContext */
/***/ (function(__webpack_module__, __webpack_exports__, __webpack_require__) {

"use strict";
__webpack_require__.r(__webpack_exports__);
/* harmony export (binding) */ __webpack_require__.d(__webpack_exports__, "LazyContext", function() { return LazyContext; });
/* harmony import */ var react__WEBPACK_IMPORTED_MODULE_0__ = __webpack_require__(/*! react */ "react");

var LazyContext = /* non-default import from non-esm module */undefined({ strict: false });

/***/ }),
```

The expected call to `createContext` has been replaced by a call to `undefined` in the bundle which naturally fails at runtime.

__Edit:__ I've found 300+ cases where this snippet of bundle code appears: `/* non-default import from non-esm module */undefined(` so the problem is not limited to just that one location. All seem to occur in .mjs files.

Any ideas on what's causing this and how to prevent it?

